<div class="row pad-all">
	<div class="col-md-6 col-xs-12">
		<img class="img-responsive pad-all" src="http://placehold.it/400/600">
	</div>
	<div class="col-md-6 col-xs-12">
		<div class="pad-all">
			<p>Visiting Uganda for the first time can be overwhelming.</p>
			<p>We arrange an initial one or two night stay with Mama Kendra in Jinja to help our volunteers settle in to Uganda life with a hot shower, a few beers and a dozen or so puppies. Kendra has the biggest heart of anyone we know and runs a puppy rescue in Jinja town. She spends her days training and caring for dozens of puppies, training Ugandans to properly care for pups and helping out almost anyone who crosses her threshold looking for compassion.</p>
			<p>As such Kendra's world is a whirlwind and we can't promise that your stay will not involve a trip to the vets, not-quite-housetrained-pups or a fast-tracked course in Uganda life. But if you're in Uganda and you need a friend, Kendra's quite the lady to know. She will give you all the advice and contacts you need for your stay including where to buy the best chicken-on-a-stick, the phone number of a friendly chap who runs safaris and the very best emergency doctor (and everything in between).</p>
			<p>Typically Kendra will arrange transport for you from Entebbe airport to her home. After you have acclimatised, Chris will meet you at Kendra's house and drive you to Nakamini village which is about 70km away.</p>
			<p>Also, when you see Kendra, give her a hug from us :)</p>
		</div>
